WEBVTT

00:02.700 --> 00:04.300
these are intense.
Are any of these yours?

00:04.400 --> 00:07.800
No, they're my grad students'
from my masters portfolio class.

00:08.100 --> 00:10.800
Wow, you really look beautiful in this light.

00:11.100 --> 00:14.600
Wishful thinking on both our parts.
It's a model, not me.

00:14.900 --> 00:16.500
Some photos down there you might enjoy.

00:16.700 --> 00:18.500
Student of mine was in bangladesh.

00:18.600 --> 00:21.000
Well, I'll tell you what I used to tell my mother
when I didn't finish my dinner--

00:21.100 --> 00:23.900
I don't care about kids from india,
I just care about you.

00:24.000 --> 00:26.000
I didn't say the last part to my mother.
That'd be weird.

00:26.100 --> 00:28.300
- Although I'm sure she was fascinating.
- She was, very.

00:28.400 --> 00:30.800
But no mother issues here at all.

00:33.900 --> 00:35.100
These have to be yours.

00:35.200 --> 00:37.400
This is, uh, what,
your apartment down in the east village?

00:37.500 --> 00:39.300
Do you miss it, the whole bohemian lifestyle?

00:39.400 --> 00:41.100
No, I like teaching here just fine.

00:41.200 --> 00:43.500
How come there's no pictures of you here at all?

00:43.600 --> 00:44.600
Come on, rick.

00:44.700 --> 00:47.200
It's the command performance for the new dean.
We're already late.

00:47.600 --> 00:50.000
Ok. So much for small talk.

00:51.600 --> 00:52.600
This is amazing.

00:52.700 --> 00:55.300
Just 'cause the dean is former ivy,
they rent out an entire restaurant.

00:55.400 --> 00:57.000
You know what I got when I came to rockland U.?

00:57.100 --> 00:59.600
I got a welcome packet with a few take-out menus.

00:59.700 --> 01:01.000
Professor pollili.

01:01.100 --> 01:04.200
Hi. I'm stacey adler. Not that it matters.

01:04.300 --> 01:08.100
I know your work. I've tried to get into
your classes, but they fill up so fast.

01:08.200 --> 01:10.800
Well, it's very nice to meet you, stacey.
This is professor payne.

01:10.900 --> 01:13.000
Oh, great. 
I'm going to get the spelling in just a sec.

01:13.200 --> 01:14.300
Oh, no, please.

01:14.400 --> 01:17.000
Oh, it's just a P.R. Picture 
for the university magazine.

01:17.100 --> 01:18.300
No. I said no.

01:19.200 --> 01:21.200
I'm sorry. I just-- please, don'T.

01:21.300 --> 01:23.900
Ok. I'm-- I didn't realize. Sorry.

01:24.700 --> 01:26.100
I can't do this.

01:26.500 --> 01:28.700
- I thought I could, but I can'T.
- What? What can't you do?

01:28.800 --> 01:30.500
Look, it's not you. I just--

01:30.600 --> 01:33.300
I really don't feel well,
so I'm going to go. Um...

01:36.000 --> 01:38.600
- that is weird.
- Yeah, that's weird.

01:38.700 --> 01:41.800
I know. I had her right in frame.

01:42.200 --> 01:46.100
Wow. That is weird.
Can I borrow this for a second?

01:46.200 --> 01:47.500
Actually, like, right now, this second.

01:47.600 --> 01:50.100
It's ok. I'm a professor.

01:53.500 --> 01:56.600
- Ok. Thank you very much.
- Wait. Why?

01:56.900 --> 02:00.400
Because you just gave your memory card
to the anthropology department.

02:00.500 --> 02:01.700
I appreciate it.

02:01.800 --> 02:03.700
But--wh-what about the magazine?

02:03.800 --> 02:07.700
Use your descriptive powers.
Why, you know, cheat with pictures?

02:11.900 --> 02:13.200
Hello!

02:13.300 --> 02:15.700
I know you guys are home. I can see your cars.

02:15.800 --> 02:17.800
- Are you expecting someone?
- No one!

02:17.900 --> 02:19.200
Hello?

02:19.300 --> 02:21.100
Hello, hello, hello!

02:21.900 --> 02:24.000
Hello.

02:24.300 --> 02:25.700
Hey. How are you, jim?

02:25.800 --> 02:27.500
You been working out? You look good.

02:27.600 --> 02:30.300
There she is.
Ahh. This is nice.

02:30.400 --> 02:32.800
There's the missus, a nice crackling fire.

02:32.900 --> 02:36.200
Nice vintage-- a little pricey.
"Scrupulistic" not a word.

02:36.300 --> 02:37.400
Didn't you have a date tonight?

02:37.500 --> 02:38.700
I did have a date tonight,

02:38.800 --> 02:42.200
as it were, since you're the one that
forced me back into the dating world.

02:42.400 --> 02:45.100
- What happened?
- Well, what happened? I'll tell you what happened.

02:45.200 --> 02:46.641
This might have been the first time in my life 

02:46.741 --> 02:51.801
that a woman said
 "it's not you, it's me," and I believed her.

02:51.900 --> 02:52.900
Let me find these for you.

02:53.000 --> 02:55.400
Oh, here's professor reeman, russian studies.

02:55.500 --> 02:58.300
He just got published... again.

02:58.500 --> 03:00.100
Ok. Oh, here we are. Ok. That's me.

03:00.200 --> 03:03.200
Wow. This really is...a damn fine suit.

03:03.300 --> 03:06.100
That's me, and next to me,
that's where my date should be.

03:06.200 --> 03:08.500
That big, empty space, that's where my date was. Ok?

03:08.600 --> 03:11.000
Here's another one.
That's me sitting next to...

03:11.100 --> 03:13.600
ehh, no one. Nothing's there. Ok.

03:13.700 --> 03:16.900
Oh. Here's claudia's exit, 
which was abrupt, to say the least,

03:17.000 --> 03:19.500
although you can't see it on any of these photos

03:19.600 --> 03:20.900
'cause apparently, she doesn't exist.

03:21.000 --> 03:22.500
Let me take a look at that.

03:22.600 --> 03:24.500
So she's not showing up in any of the photos.

03:24.600 --> 03:27.200
Just admit it, melinda--
tonight, I got dumped by a ghost.

03:27.400 --> 03:29.700
- Does she even exist?
- Yes. She has tenure.

03:29.800 --> 03:32.800
It's publish or perish.
Her photographs are published everywhere.

03:32.900 --> 03:34.300
But she's not in any of them,

03:34.400 --> 03:37.000
and nor have I seen her
in any of her personal photography,

03:37.100 --> 03:39.700
and the photos she has of herself on her desk
with her family and things--

03:39.800 --> 03:41.500
nothing. She's not in any photos.

03:41.600 --> 03:42.800
Well, that's weird.

03:42.900 --> 03:46.600
I mean, maybe it's something about her energy,
or something the camera can't capture.

03:46.700 --> 03:50.700
I don't think so. Paranormal occurrences
usually work the opposite way.

03:50.800 --> 03:55.500
Spirits are visible in photographs
because cameras detect light and heat.

03:55.600 --> 03:59.300
But a broader spectrum of energy
the human eye can't detect.

03:59.400 --> 04:00.100
Kind of like that?

04:00.500 --> 04:03.300
Ok. I've never seen this before.

04:03.500 --> 04:05.200
Hang on a second.

04:05.400 --> 04:07.100
It's with her in every shot.

04:07.200 --> 04:09.400
For the record, that's not who I asked out.

04:09.500 --> 04:11.300
Maybe not, but...

04:11.400 --> 04:13.600
that's who went home with her.

